Playing the raw data of a WebAssembly (WASM) file directly as sound isn't typically straightforward, because WASM files contain compiled binary code, not sound wave data. However, if for some context we consider performing experimental audio synthesis by interpreting the binary data as audio samples, one way to achieve a sound output would be to read the raw WASM binary data and interpret it as raw audio data.

Here's a theoretical example of how you might do it using JavaScript in a browser environment. Note that this is an esoteric way to produce sound and will likely create noise rather than any structured music or sounds:

```javascript
// assuming you have your WASM binary data as an ArrayBuffer
fetch('path_to_your.wasm')
    .then(response => response.arrayBuffer())
    .then(arrayBuffer => {
        const audioContext = new AudioContext();
        const audioBuffer = audioContext.createBuffer(1, arrayBuffer.byteLength, audioContext.sampleRate);

        // Now fill the buffer with your WASM binary data
        // This assumes the data can be interpreted as PCM data, which is unlikely
        const channelData = audioBuffer.getChannelData(0);
        const view = new Uint8Array(arrayBuffer);
        for (let i = 0; i < arrayBuffer.byteLength; i++) {
            // Normalize the data between -1.0 and 1.0 as required for audio samples
            channelData[i] = (view[i] - 128) / 128.0;
        }

        // Create a buffer source node
        const source = audioContext.createBufferSource();
        source.buffer = audioBuffer;

        // Connect the source to the context's destination (the speakers)
        source.connect(audioContext.destination);

        // Start the source playing
        source.start();
    })
    .catch(console.error);
```

This example treats the binary data as raw 8-bit PCM audio data, which requires normalization from 0-255 to -1.0 to 1.0 (values for audio signals in Web Audio API). This will almost certainly result in a blast of noise because WASM binary data is not intended to represent audio signals.

It's important to carefully control the volume when experimenting with this, as it could potentially be very loud or unpleasant. Keep in mind that this approach may not be meaningful or useful in any conventional sense, as the resulting sound would just be a playback of binary data that wasn't actually designed to be audio.

The message you're seeing is related to an autoplay policy enforced by modern browsers to improve the user experience by preventing audio from automatically playing without the user's consent. To start the `AudioContext`, you need to initiate it in response to a user interaction, such as a button click.

Here’s an updated version of the code that starts the `AudioContext` only after a user gesture:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Play WASM Data As Sound</title>
</head>
<body>
    <button id="playSound">Play Sound</button>

    <script>
        // This button click event will allow us to resume the AudioContext
        document.getElementById('playSound').addEventListener('click', () => {
            const audioContext = new AudioContext();

            fetch('path_to_your.wasm')
                .then(response => response.arrayBuffer())
                .then(arrayBuffer => {
                    const audioBuffer = audioContext.createBuffer(1, arrayBuffer.byteLength, audioContext.sampleRate);
                    const channelData = audioBuffer.getChannelData(0);
                    const view = new Uint8Array(arrayBuffer);

