    var audioContext = new AudioContext();
    // ...
    fetch('path_to_your.wasm').then(function(response) {
        // ...
    }).then(function(arrayBuffer) {
        // Perform previous operations
        //...

        // Start playing the sound
        source.start();

        // Create WAV download link when source stops
        source.onended = function() {
            // Use audiobuffer-to-wav library to convert the AudioBuffer to WAV
            var wav = toWav(audioBuffer);
            var blob = new Blob([new DataView(wav)], {
                type: 'audio/wav'
            });

            var url = URL.createObjectURL(blob);
            var anchor = document.createElement('a');
            anchor.href = url;
            anchor.download = 'audio.wav';
            anchor.textContent = 'Download WAV';
            anchor.click();

            // Remove object URL after downloading
            URL.revokeObjectURL(url);
        };

    }).catch(console.error);

    //...
});
```

In the example above, we use the `toWav` function provided by the `audiobuffer-to-wav` library to handle the proper conversion of the `AudioBuffer` to a WAVE file format before creating a download link.

Make sure to reference the correct path to the `audiobuffer-to-wav.js` script, which you can find at: https://github.com/Jam3/audiobuffer-to-wav

And don't forget you'll need to trigger the download after the audio has finished playing, or when the user takes an action to initiate the download. Since this script uses the `source.onended` event, this means the download will not be available until after the sound has stopped playing. Alternatively, you can create a separate button to trigger the download when clicked.

Raw data noise involves taking arbitrary binary data, which is not designed to represent audio, and playing it back as audio to produce noise. This can be done for artistic, experimental, or analytical purposes, and it often results in atonal, harsh, or chaotic sounds because binary data does not follow the rules of music or structured sound design.

When we interpret binary data from files like WebAssembly modules, executable files, or even images, as audio waveforms, we're effectively treating bytes as audio sample values. Since these bytes were never intended to model sound waves, the resulting audio is generally perceived as noise.

To play raw data from a WASM file as sound, you can use the Web Audio API in a web browser. Here's a step-by-step guide:

1. **Fetch the WASM File**: Load your WASM file into memory as an `ArrayBuffer`.

2. **Create an Audio Buffer**: Generate an `AudioBuffer` from the `ArrayBuffer`. You'll need to decide how to map the binary data to audio samples. A typical approach is to treat the data as a sequence of signed or unsigned integers and normalize them to the -1.0 to 1.0 range expected by the audio system.

3. **Play the Buffer**: Use an `AudioBufferSourceNode` to play the `AudioBuffer`.

Here's a full example of how you might achieve this:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Raw Data Noise Generator</title>
</head>
<body>
    <button id="playButton">Play Noise</button>

    <script>
        document.getElementById('playButton').addEventListener('click', function() {
            // Initialize the AudioContext
            var audioContext = new AudioContext();

            // Fetch the WebAssembly binary as an ArrayBuffer
            fetch('path_to_your.wasm')
                .then(function(response) {
                    return response.arrayBuffer();
                })
                .then(function(arrayBuffer) {
                    // Create an audio buffer with 1 channel, length of the arrayBuffer,
                    // and sample rate of the audio context
                    var audioBuffer = audioContext.createBuffer(1, arrayBuffer.byteLength, audioContext.sampleRate);
                    var channelData = audioBuffer.getChannelData(0);
                    var byteView = new Uint8Array(arrayBuffer);

                    // Fill the audio buffer with normalized data from the byte array
                    for (var i = 0; i < arrayBuffer.byteLength; i++) {
                        // Normalize the unsigned byte value to a float in the range of -1.0 to 1.0
                        channelData[i] = (byteView[i] - 128) / 128.0;
                    }

                    // Create a buffer source node and set the buffer
                    var source = audioContext.createBufferSource();
                    source.buffer = audioBuffer;
                    source.loop = true; // Optionally loop the noise

                    // Connect the source to the audio context's destination
                    source.connect(audioContext.destination);

                    // Start playing the sound
                    source.start();

                    // Optionally store the source node to stop playback later
                    window.audioSource = source;
                })
                .catch(function(error) {
                    console.error('Error fetching or processing the WASM file:', error);
                });
        });

        // Handle stopping the noise
        document.getElementById('stopButton').addEventListener('click', function() {
            if (window.audioSource) {
                window.audioSource.stop();
            }
        });
    </script>

    <button id="stopButton">Stop Noise</button>
</body>
</html>
```

